{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17640566","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17640566"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:18:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:18:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17837"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17837","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17837"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.41,0.05,0.09,0.41,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10551"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116731"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10551","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10551"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17837"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98718"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10059"},{"type":"tags","id":"10475"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24605"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24608"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116731","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116731"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is correct regarding the entry of carbohydrates into the intestinal mucosa?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Glucose enters via GLUT2","Fructose enters via SGLT1","Galactose enters via GLUT5","Glucose enters via SGLT1","Galactose enters via GLUT2"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlucose enters via SGLT1\u003C/strong\u003E, which is a sodium-dependent glucose transporter located in the small intestine. It facilitates the active transport of glucose and galactose into the intestinal mucosa cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGalactose enters via GLUT5\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Galactose, like glucose, is absorbed via SGLT1, not GLUT5. GLUT5 is specific for fructose transport.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFructose enters via SGLT1\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Fructose is absorbed via GLUT5, a transporter specific for fructose, not glucose or galactose.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlucose enters via GLUT2\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. While GLUT2 is involved in the transport of glucose out of the enterocytes into the bloodstream, glucose initially enters the intestinal mucosa via SGLT1.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGalactose enters via GLUT2\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Similar to glucose, galactose is initially absorbed via SGLT1, and GLUT2 is involved in its transport out of the enterocytes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Glucose and galactose are absorbed in the small intestine via specific transporters.","SGLT1 is a sodium-dependent glucose transporter responsible for the uptake of glucose and galactose.","GLUT5 is a transporter specific for fructose, not glucose or galactose."],"references":["Bender DA, Cunningham SM. Introduction to nutrition and metabolism. CRC Press; 2021.","Salway JG. Metabolism at a Glance. John Wiley \u0026 Sons; 2016.","Chandel NS. Carbohydrate Metabolism. Cold Spring Harb Perspect Biol. 2021;13(1):a040568.","Hall JE. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2021. Chapter 66, pg. 831."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98718"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17837"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"